<HEADLINE>
GOVERNMENT PROVIDES NT$1.72 BILLION TO AID OVER 900,000 POOR
CHILDREN
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Taipei,  March 25 (CNA) 03/25/07  18:29:18 (By Y.L. Kao)
</P>
<P>
The government offered NT$1.72 billion (US$52.12 million) cash
subsidies to help more than 900,000 children from impoverished
families in 2006, among whom 1,354 suffered domestic violence, an
increase of 20 percent according to tallies released by the
Directorate-General of Budget, Accounting and Statics (DGBAS).
</P>
<P>
The government is providing living subsidies to children and
teenagers from low and middle income households qualified by
"Social Assistance Law", including those from single-parent
families, and whose parents are deceased, seriously ill, or
imprisoned for a definite term of over one year, the report
offered by the Ministry of Interior showed.
</P>
<P>
The standard subsidy to low income families was adjusted annually
according to relevant regulations on minimum of subsistence
allowance for residents in every city and county around the
country, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
Taking Taipei City for example, children from low-income families
are eligible to receive subsidies of NT$ 5,000 based on the
minimal living standard amount of NT$14,000 announced in the
city.
</P>
<P>
According to the tallies, 900,850 children and teenagers received
government cash subsidies for low-income families in 2006, an
increase of 9.2 percent year- on-year. the tallies showed, among
them, 882,508 were grouped into "ordinary" category, representing
an annual increasing  of 9.4 percent,  while 18,342 were
identified  as "aboriginal people".
</P>
<P>
A total of 2,031 children and adolescents were sent to foster
families in 2006, of whom, more than half, 1,354 were so placed
due to suffering abuse, the tallies showed.
</P>
